    <h1>Delivering Stage One:</h1>
    <h2>The Trinity College Dublin Prototype</h2>

    <p><strong>The first stage of the Dot-Public rollout is the creation of a Minimum Viable Product
            (MVP)</strong> developed in partnership with Trinity College Dublin (TCD). This partnership provides
        a credible, scholarly, and technically capable anchor for the prototype phase, grounding the
        project in an institution whose reputation is built on trust, rigour, and long-term stewardship
        of knowledge.</p>

    <p>The purpose of the MVP is not to build a miniature version of the full Dot-Public system, but
        to create a functioning testbed for its core components. It will demonstrate that the proposed
        civic layer can coexist with the open internet and validate the operational, technical, and
        governance models required for long-term sustainability.</p>

    <p>Using trusted academic and cultural material from Ireland’s seven core universities (digitised
        monographs, doctoral theses, archival collections, peer-reviewed journals, curated
        exhibitions), it will provide a controlled, but representative, environment to test civic-grade
        standards, integrity, provenance, and public value.</p>

    <p>The prototype will serve as a live laboratory to test and refine the three foundational pillars of
        Dot-Public, in order to demonstrate:</p>

    <ol>
        <li><strong>The Civic Boundary</strong>: Services defined by civic values can be built, maintained and
            accessed within a distinct provisioned namespace.</li>

        <li><strong>The Civic Contract</strong>: Meaningful governance rules can be developed, adopted and
            tested in practice, with real institutions and real users.</li>

        <li><strong>The Civic Experience</strong>: The concepts behind clean tools for Trust, Provenance, and
            universal Accessibility can be made tangible.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Scope and Structure of the MVP</h3>
    <p>The MVP will be structured around four integrated testbeds, each designed to establish and
        also de-risk essential elements of the full-scale system.</p>

    <ol>
        <li>
            <strong>Domain Testbed</strong>: To establish and manage the technical foundation of the civicboundary.
            <ul>
                <li>Creation of a provisional, trusted namespace (e.g., public.tcd.ie) to
                    simulate the .PUBLIC gTLD.</li>
                <li>Implementation of robust security protocols, including DNSSEC, to
                    ensure integrity.</li>
                <li>Establishment of a registry for participating services and enforcement
                    of privacy-by-default principles.</li>
                <li>Development and testing of technical mechanisms for displaying
                    provenance indicators at the domain level.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Governance Testbed</strong>: To pilot the governance and compliance model outlined in
            the Civic Contract.
            <ul>
                <li>Establishment of a pilot Governance Body at TCD with representation
                    from faculty, students, library/archives, and external civic advisers.</li>
                <li>Drafting, ratification, and adoption of the first version of the Dot-Public
                    Civic Contract, defining eligibility, obligations, and oversight
                    procedures.</li>
                <li>Live-testing of compliance audits and enforcement mechanisms with
                    real institutional services and user groups.</li>
                <li>Development of a transparent process for handling appeals and
                    third-party challenges.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Reference Models Testbed</strong>: To build and demonstrate key reference services that embody
            Dot-Public values.
            <ul>
                <li>Civic Search Prototype: Development of a search tool that indexes
                    only the pilot namespace, prioritises results based on provenance and
                    authority, and surfaces transparency indicators.</li>
                <li>Clean Tools Suite: Creation of an initial set of developer tools to audit
                    sites for compliance, exposing inadvertent code violations, tracking
                    elements, and accessibility issues.</li>
                <li>Trusted Archive Service: TCD Library and Archives will provision a
                    significant dataset (e.g., digitised special collections, theses, research
                    data) within the [.public.tcd.ie] domain, serving as a live example of
                    verifiable provenance and permanent, equitable access.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Civic Experience Testbed</strong>: To design and validate the user-facing signals of trust.
            <ul>
                <li>
                    Development of a coherent design language and visual system for the
                    .PUBLIC domain, including trust marks, provenance indicators, and
                    accessibility badges.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Creation of a civic portal that explains the Dot-Public principles to
                    users and gathers feedback.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Rigorous usability testing with students, faculty, and public participants
                    to evaluate the clarity and effectiveness of trust signals.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ol>


    <h3>MVP Delivery Phases</h3>
    <p>The development of the prototype will be delivered in four discrete phases:</p>

    <ul>
        <li>
            Phase 1: Discovery (3 months)
            <ul>
                <li>Identify the technical architecture and governance framework.</li>
                <li>Identify and inventory specific TCD/IUA systems and services for inclusion.</li>
                <li>Convene the Governance Working Group</li>
                <li>Define precise success metrics.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            Phase 2: Build (6 months)
            <ul>
                <li>Stand up the provisional namespace and registry.</li>
                <li>Develop, adopt and deploy the reference services (Civic search, clean tools, trusted archive).</li>
                <li>Draft and approve the first-level Civic Contract.</li>
                <li>Design first-pass Trust and Provenance indicators.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            Phase 3: Test &amp; Evaluate (3 months)
            <ul>
                <li>Conduct a controlled pilot with defined user groups (students, faculty, external
                    testers).</li>
                <li>Evaluate usability, governance functionality, technical resilience, and user
                    trust.</li>
                <li>Produce independent assessment reports on both technical and civic
                    performance.</li>
                <li>Refine the above based on findings</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            Phase 4: Report &amp; Scale (2 months)
            <ul>
                <li>
                    Use findings to produce a public report: i.e. what worked, what failed, what is
                    going to be required to achieve scale.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Formalise the proposal and business case for Stage Two national expansion
                    within Ireland.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>

