    <h3>Success criteria for prototype</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>
            A functioning namespace with basic provenance enforcement.
        </li>
        <li>
            At least two working reference services in .PUBLIC.
        </li>
        <li>
            A published civic contract adopted by participants.
        </li>
        <li>
            A governance sandbox that has exercised decision-making and enforcement.
        </li>
        <li>
            Evidence from users that trust signals are visible and meaningful.
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Why Trinity College, Dublin?</h3>

    <p>Dot-Public is not only a technical experiment, it is an act of institutional leadership. The
        decision to begin this work at Trinity College Dublin is not incidental. It reflects the
        recognition that universities are both custodians of trusted knowledge and laboratories for
        the creation of new civic infrastructure. By anchoring the first prototype in an academic
        environment, Dot-Public is grounded in the very values it seeks to enforce online:
        provenance, rigour, accessibility, and trust.</p>

    <p>The immediate focus of the prototype is practical. It will build a working model that allows
        verifiable academic and cultural data to be published within a bounded, rule-governed
        space. Academic datasets will provide the first test corpus, and the technical, legal, and
        governance mechanisms needed to sustain this layer will be explored in parallel. This is not
        yet a system for everyone, but a proof that such a system can exist, and that it can be done
        credibly, affordably, and sustainably.</p>

    <p>Yet the implications extend far beyond the walls of Trinity. Around the world, governments,
        technologists, and civic institutions are converging on the idea of Digital Public Infrastructure:
        shared systems for identity, payments, records, and services. Ireland, through Trinity, has
        the opportunity to take a visible role in this global movement, positioning itself as a credible,
        neutral host of civic standards for the internet age.</p>

    <p>For Trinity itself, the benefits are threefold. First, it affirms the University’s scholarly mission
        by improving the discoverability and veracity of research material. Second, it strengthens
        Trinity’s convening power, placing it at the centre of an international conversation about
        digital public goods. Third, it allows Trinity to lead by example, not only studying the problem
        of civic trust online, but actively building a solution that others can adopt, adapt, and benefit
        from.</p>

    <p>The MVP is therefore more than a prototype. It is the first step in demonstrating how a
        university can act as an incubator for global civic infrastructure. By combining technical
        delivery with governance exploration and scholarly rigour, Trinity and Dot-Public together can
        set a precedent for how public institutions shape, rather than follow, the digital environment.</p>

